08745nam a22009495i 9780226506869DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017013691  a97802265068697 a10.7208/97802265068692doi  a(DE-B1597)550179  a(OCoLC)1012126302  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQE719.8b.C66 2017 4aQE719 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a56022300aConservation Paleobiology :bScience and Practice /ced. by Karl W. Flessa, Gregory P. Dietl. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b60 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tSection One. Conservation Paleobiology in Near Time -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. The youngest fossil record and conservation biology: Holocene shells as eco-environmental recorders -- tChapter Two. Conservation biology and environmental change: A paleolimnological perspective -- tChapter Three. Vertebrate fossils and the future of conservation biology -- tChapter Four Paleoecology and resource management in a dynamic landscape: Case studies from the Rocky Mountain headwaters -- tChapter Five Historical ecology for the paleontologist -- tChapter Six The isotopic ecology of fossil vertebrates and conservation paleobiology -- tChapter Seven Evaluating human modification of shallow marine ecosystems: Mismatch in composition of molluscan living and time-averaged death assemblages -- tChapter Eight Using a macroecological approach to the fossil record to help inform conservation biology -- tSection Two Conservation Paleobiology in Deep Time -- tIntroduction -- tChapter Nine Seven variations on a recent theme of conservation -- tChapter Ten Metaphor, inference, and prediction in paleoecology: Climate change and the Antarctic bottom fauna -- tChapter Eleven Ecological modeling of paleocommunity food webs -- tChapter Twelve Paleobiology and the conservation of the evolving web of life -- tChapter Thirteen Speciation and shifting baselines: Prospects for reciprocal illumination between evolutionary paleobiology and conservation biology -- tSection Three Conservation Paleobiology at Work -- tIntroduction -- tChapter Fourteen Putting the dead to work: Translational paleoecology -- tChapter Fifteen Conservation paleobiology roundtable: From promise to application -- tEpilogue Conservation Paleobiology in the Anthropocene -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn conservation, perhaps no better example exists of the past informing the present than the return of the California condor to the Vermilion Cliffs of Arizona. Extinct in the region for nearly one hundred years, condors were successfully reintroduced starting in the 1990s in an effort informed by the fossil record—condor skeletal remains had been found in the area’s late-Pleistocene cave deposits. The potential benefits of applying such data to conservation initiatives are unquestionably great, yet integrating the relevant disciplines has proven challenging. Conservation Paleobiology gathers a remarkable array of scientists—from Jeremy B. C. Jackson to Geerat J. Vermeij—to provide an authoritative overview of how paleobiology can inform both the management of threatened species and larger conservation decisions. Studying endangered species is difficult. They are by definition rare, some exist only in captivity, and for those still in their native habitats any experimentation can potentially have a negative effect on survival. Moreover, a lack of long-term data makes it challenging to anticipate biotic responses to environmental conditions that are outside of our immediate experience. But in the fossil and prefossil records—from natural accumulations such as reefs, shell beds, and caves to human-made deposits like kitchen middens and archaeological sites—enlightening parallels to the Anthropocene can be found that might serve as a primer for present-day predicaments. Offering both deep-time and near-time perspectives and exploring a range of ecological and evolutionary dynamics and taxa from terrestrial as well as aquatic habitats, Conservation Paleobiology is a sterling demonstration of how the past can be used to manage for the future, giving new hope for the creation and implementation of successful conservation programs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aConservation biology. 0aPaleobiology. 0aPaleoecology. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  abiodiversity.  aconservation science.  aecoystem services.  afossil record.  apaleontology.  aresource management.  arestoration.1 aAllmon, Warren D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAronson, Richard B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnosky, Anthony D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyer, Alison G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrenner, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurney, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDietl, Gregory P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDietl, Gregory P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFlessa, Karl W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlessa, Karl W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFox-Dobbs, Kena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Stephen T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHadly, Elizabeth A., 